commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Change-Id: Ifeaf89f0f7314d442112452ed1649a3694901271
Story: #2002586
Task: #24296

commit_message:
Catch MAASConfigIncomplete and set workload message

validate_dns_ha() shouldn't have the side effect of setting the workload
status and message, so now it will raise MAASConfigIncomplete with a
message and ha_relation_changed() is catching the exception, setting the
workload in blocked status and short circuiting the hook execution until
the user set maas_url and maas_credentials.

Change-Id: I3f1bc6571d2461cb65f384f042423cfe33f4d2f8
Closes-Bug: 1790559

commit_message:
Fixing /var/run/ceph/ directory permissions

In previous versions of the charm the directory /var/run/ceph/
was created with access permissions only for root.
Consequently libvirt had no access to the rbd admin socket.

Prior installations are also fixed through update-charm.

Change-Id: I7f8054a404de9910bc070b288e1df1ce8dcf754e
Closes-Bug: #1779676

messages:
[{'account_id': 4727, 'date': '2018-08-26 02:58:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 23567, 'date': '2018-08-27 06:50:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Looks like just a rebase from No.7 to No.9, no substantial change.'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2018-08-14 08:13:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)

Sorry, honesty I don't like to block this one but with my dignity, I set my -1 here for the following 2 reasons.

1. I'm feeling the "-N" for Swift native slo is painful and makes us complex to maintain. It's not following actual S3 but it's expected to be used via s3 client if this patch get merged. Though I don't much understand how the s3client deal with dash for identifying the multipart object, hard coded "-N" that is not the S3 spec might cause any errors in the future. Possibly, collecting -<# of part in the manifest> on time of the request would be the best compatibility rather than just setting -N.

2. ListingETagMiddleware is not tested completely. I believe that affects native Swift request (for objects written by S3API) so absolutely we must add the tests (at least unit tests) to assert nothing broken for native Swift APIs. And hopefully, I'd like re-use (or refactor) ListingFormats middleware that keeps much duplicate codes to do small adjustment of s3_etag.

What I can recommend here to get this improve immediately is focusing only on "the complete multipart upload" that add s3_etag in the object listing, and translate it only in S3 world. Then, consider/discuss other staffs like cross-API compatibility and listing formats in later patches.

How do you feel it?'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-08-14 17:25:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(8 comments)

I'll look at trying to break this up a bit.

---

> how the s3client deal with dash for identifying the multipart object

In aws-sdk-java, it really is a straight check for '-' [1] which (eventually, tortuously [2] [3]) gates an MD5-check [4].

In s3cmd, the MD5 gets computed and stored during upload [5] [6] [7]. When it sees a '-' in a listing [8], it'll do a HEAD to look for it [9] so it can compare both size and MD5 when syncing [10].

[1] https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-java/blob/1.11.386/aws-java-sdk-s3/src/main/java/com/amazonaws/services/s3/internal/SkipMd5CheckStrategy.java#L261-L271
[2] https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-java/blob/1.11.386/aws-java-sdk-s3/src/main/java/com/amazonaws/services/s3/internal/SkipMd5CheckStrategy.java#L215-L225
[3] https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-java/blob/1.11.386/aws-java-sdk-s3/src/main/java/com/amazonaws/services/s3/internal/SkipMd5CheckStrategy.java#L48-L66
[4] https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-java/blob/1.11.386/aws-java-sdk-s3/src/main/java/com/amazonaws/services/s3/internal/ServiceUtils.java#L320-L338

[5] https://github.com/s3tools/s3cmd/blob/v2.0.2/s3cmd#L417-L419
[6] https://github.com/s3tools/s3cmd/blob/v2.0.2/s3cmd#L1665-L1668
[7] https://github.com/s3tools/s3cmd/blob/v2.0.2/s3cmd#L1584-L1596
[8] https://github.com/s3tools/s3cmd/blob/v2.0.2/S3/FileLists.py#L431-L432
[9] https://github.com/s3tools/s3cmd/blob/v2.0.2/S3/FileLists.py#L357-L372
[10] https://github.com/s3tools/s3cmd/blob/v2.0.2/S3/FileLists.py#L523-L543

> hard coded "-N" that is not the S3 spec might cause any errors in the future

Yeah, it's not great, but FWIW I've only ever seen checks for the presence or absence of a dash, never any validations about the rest of the format. Limited sample size, YMMV, etc. ...

> Possibly, collecting -<# of part in the manifest> on time of the request would be the best compatibility rather than just setting -N.

I suppose... but I've got a few issues with that:

- it would mean having SLO record information that's only going to (maybe) be used by s3api
- it doesn't do anything to help with data already on disk
- it would confuse the actual-S3-style ETag with the SLO-ETag-with-number-of-segments ETag

> I believe that affects native Swift request (for objects written by S3API)

Yep, it certainly does. I wanted to ensure that the s3_etag param came back out of the hash value in container listings; that's why it required a separate filter'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-08-15 22:34:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-08-15 22:34:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Workflow-1

Minor clean-up before splitting out the '-N' work."}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2018-08-16 04:57:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(2 comments)

it lookis like Tim is still working on the separation of this patch, so leave a few comments that I was thinking yesterday.

To note, I believe, adding -<number of parts> for *S3 API requests* is the first fix for the compatibility, then, the cross compatibilities with the etag value depends on the slo(Swift)/multipart(S3) objects is still contentious.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-08-17 17:31:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2018-08-20 13:14:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2018-09-12 16:12:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I checked the cover range with the summary and matrix discussed in the PTG. Almost code looks clear to me that fixes s3api multi-upload world.

Just 2 items I'd like to fix before this get merged. I added the inlines, and pushed my code at https://review.openstack.org/602076

Hopefully you like the changes."}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-09-13 07:54:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-09-13 07:54:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2018-09-13 10:29:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2018-09-13 10:33:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

(2 comments)

Just fix the pep8 error. We discussed this enough. Some of other core reviewers already their +2s. I don't think the latest patch set far from the original direction and there are just a small cleanup, splitting patches, those are not significant change from that. That means, I believe I can add my +A for this. Let's take a single +2 goes to +A scheme in Swift upstream.

Thanks Tim to have big effort to get this done!"}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-06-15 22:04:58.000000000', 'message': 'Include '-' in multipart ETags

Multipart uploads in AWS (seem to) have ETags like:

   '"' + MD5_hex(MD5(part1) + ... + MD5(partN)) + '-' + N + '"'

On the other hand, Swift SLOs have Etags like:

   MD5_hex(MD5_hex(part1) + ... + MD5_hex(partN))

(In both examples, MD5 gets the raw 16-byte digest while MD5_hex
gets the 32-byte hex-encoded digest.)

Some clients (such as aws-sdk-java) use the presence of a dash
to decide whether to perform client-side validation of downloads.

Other clients (like s3cmd) use the presence of a dash *in bucket
listings* to decide whether or not to MD5 files locally.

Now we include a dash as well, to prevent spurious errors like

> Unable to verify integrity of data download.  Client calculated
> content hash didn't match hash calculated by Amazon S3.  The data
> may be corrupt.

For new multipart-uploads via the S3 API, the ETag that is stored will
be calculated in the same way that AWS uses. This ETag will be used in
GET/HEAD responses, bucket listings, and conditional requests via the S3
API; accessing the same object via the Swift API will use the SLO Etag.

New SLOs and pre-existing multipart-uploads may have "-N" appended to
their ETag. Note that this uses the letter "N", as the number of
segments is not known. This modified ETag will be used in key GET/HEAD
responses via the S3 API, while the original ETag will be used for:

 * object responses via the Swift API,
 * container (or bucket) listings, and
 * conditional requests via the Swift API.

Either the modified or original ETag may be used for conditional
requests via the S3 API.

Change-Id: Ibe68c44bef6c17605863e9084503e8f5dc577fab
Closes-Bug: 1522578

   '"' + MD5_hex(MD5(part1) + ... + MD5(partN)) + '-' + N + '"'

On the other hand, Swift SLOs have Etags like:

   MD5_hex(MD5_hex(part1) + ... + MD5_hex(partN))

(In both examples, MD5 gets the raw 16-byte digest while MD5_hex
gets the 32-byte hex-encoded digest.)

Some clients (such as aws-sdk-java) use the presence of a dash
to decide whether to perform client-side validation of downloads.

Other clients (like s3cmd) use the presence of a dash *in bucket
listings* to decide whether or not to MD5 files locally.

Now we include a dash as well, to prevent spurious errors like

> Unable to verify integrity of data download.  Client calculated
> content hash didn't match hash calculated by Amazon S3.  The data
> may be corrupt.

For new multipart-uploads via the S3 API, the ETag that is stored will
be calculated in the same way that AWS uses. This ETag will be used in
GET/HEAD responses, bucket listings, and conditional requests via the S3
API; accessing the same object via the Swift API will use the SLO Etag.

New SLOs and pre-existing multipart-uploads may have "-N" appended to
their ETag. Note that this uses the letter "N", as the number of
segments is not known. This modified ETag will be used in key GET/HEAD
responses via the S3 API, while the original ETag will be used for:

 * object responses via the Swift API,
 * container (or bucket) listings, and
 * conditional requests via the Swift API.

Either the modified or original ETag may be used for conditional
requests via the S3 API.

Change-Id: Ibe68c44bef6c17605863e9084503e8f5dc577fab
Closes-Bug: 1522578

commit_message:
s3api: Include '-' in multipart ETags

Multipart uploads in AWS (seem to) have ETags like:

   '"' + MD5_hex(MD5(part1) + ... + MD5(partN)) + '-' + N + '"'

On the other hand, Swift SLOs have Etags like:

   MD5_hex(MD5_hex(part1) + ... + MD5_hex(partN))

(In both examples, MD5 gets the raw 16-byte digest while MD5_hex
gets the 32-byte hex-encoded digest.)

Some clients (such as aws-sdk-java) use the presence of a dash
to decide whether to perform client-side validation of downloads.

Other clients (like s3cmd) use the presence of a dash *in bucket
listings* to decide whether or not to perform additional HEAD requests
to look for MD5 metadata that can be used to compare against the MD5s
of local files.

Now we include a dash as well, to prevent spurious errors like

> Unable to verify integrity of data download.  Client calculated
> content hash didn't match hash calculated by Amazon S3.  The data
> may be corrupt.

or unnecessary uploads/downloads because the client assumes data has
changed that hasn't.

For new multipart-uploads via the S3 API, the ETag that is stored will
be calculated in the same way that AWS uses. This ETag will be used in
GET/HEAD responses, bucket listings, and conditional requests via the S3
API. Accessing the same object via the Swift API will use the SLO Etag;
however, in JSON container listings the multipart upload etag will be
exposed in a new "s3_etag" key.

New SLOs and pre-existing multipart-uploads will continue to behave as
before; there is no data migration or mitigation as part of this patch.

Change-Id: Ibe68c44bef6c17605863e9084503e8f5dc577fab
Closes-Bug: 1522578

commit_message:
Pass sys.stdin.buffer to json.load() in Python 3

When running with Python 3 json.load() will only work with sys.stdin if
we pass there its buffer property. This commit implements that in
kuryr-cni.

Implements: blueprint goal-python36
Change-Id: Ic05f9071a792e30e56e002d9af61387a25eaa5c0
Closes-Bug: 1792191

Add support for python3 containerized kuryr-kubernetes

containers using Python3 and get it automated in devstack.

commit_message:
Consolidate add/remove router interface OVS transactions

This patch consolidades the database transactions for creating/deleting
router ports on/from the OVN NB database. Having a single transaction is
ideal to avoid inconsistencies that can be cause between two or more
transactions.

Closes-Bug: #1756388
Change-Id: I0a0a5f6571ea695b91db89170be1fab258acd917
(cherry picked from commit 378f4ec58e16a363aeabd16da1911775d0b36487)

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/600906
Change-Id: I2ce20adf933e050e7429d6876fa1f0049db4183d

[{'created': '2018-09-12 08:22:32.000000000', 'message': 'Fix how Mistral calculates workflow output

* Workflow output sometimes is not calculated correctly due to
  the race condition between different transactions: the one that
  checks workflow completion (i.e. calls "check_and_complete") and
  the one that processes action execution completion (i.e. calls
  "on_action_complete"). Calculating output sometimes was based on
  stale data cached by the SQLAlchemy session. To fix this, we just
  need to expire all objects in the session so that they are
  refreshed automatically if we read their state in order to make
  required calculations. See the bug description for more details
  on how the problem was observed.

Change-Id: I4a7e7fd9a4bbb6e93df169b4b40bc2d83ccfce89
Closes-Bug: #1792090
'}, {'created': '2018-09-12 08:28:11.000000000', 'message': 'Fix how Mistral calculates workflow output

commit_message:
Fix how Mistral calculates workflow output

* Workflow output sometimes is not calculated correctly due to
  the race condition between different transactions: the one that
  checks workflow completion (i.e. calls "check_and_complete") and
  the one that processes action execution completion (i.e. calls
  "on_action_complete"). Calculating output sometimes was based on
  stale data cached by the SQLAlchemy session. To fix this, we just
  need to expire all objects in the session so that they are
  refreshed automatically if we read their state in order to make
  required calculations. See the bug description for more details
  on how the problem was observed.
* Added another test for direct workflow that formally checks
  calculation of workflow output. It doesn't pretend to test the
  aforementioned issue (it can be reproduced only with a big number
  of attempts, and/or under load). It's for the sake of the test
  module completeness.

Change-Id: I4a7e7fd9a4bbb6e93df169b4b40bc2d83ccfce89
Closes-Bug: #1792090

Update .zuul.yaml

Make cover job voting as it's done in the openstack-cover-jobs template.

anymore with current publish-openstack-docs-pti setup and use of
doc/requirements. Remove the individual jobs that are now duplicated.

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that

Change-Id: I4b9e7fa63cea99deefb6abdfe030a404cfa3d3aa
'}]
commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I4b9e7fa63cea99deefb6abdfe030a404cfa3d3aa

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:

commit_message:
pipeline: remove transformer support

Transformers cannot work correctly on multiple nodes without workload
partitioning, which has been removed.
The transformation of data is no more the responsability of Ceilometer. The
data storage used by default (Gnocchi), is able to handle the scenario that
Ceilometer covered by default such as computing the rate of a metric.

Change-Id: If3683318b998a37c40bc09314dd8ab3eef326ba7
Depends-On: Ifd1d04ce813028f115c19bc983e7dd1e63c6f8a5
Depends-On: I0330c09d72c20d63d08770b52d3071512a418260

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Change-Id: I756e2fde7a70682f079c477e9a9c426e3605f5f2
Story: #2002586
Task: #24346

commit_message:
Update placeholder text of the searchbar

The placeholder text of the searchbar, "Click here for filters",
makes users unaware that they could also do full text search.
It was suggested to change it to
"Click here for filters or full text search"

Translation of the text needs to be updated via
https://translate.openstack.org

Change-Id: I20b09d7f8c838b333132abdc899418246261eed5
Signed-off-by: Trinh Nguyen <dangtrinhnt@gmail.com>
Story: #1633532
Task: #25263

commit_message:
Disables Django 1.10 required attribute

Removes the default 'required' attribute rendered by Django into the
hidden Selects of the ThemableDynamicTypedChoiceField widgets. This
attribute causes issues in Chrome with a new, client side validation
present in Django 1.10.

Change-Id: I6d0a2951cc74ffa57d091a4589372bf9b93cd33f
Closes-Bug: #1792127

commit_message:
Fix RST building

Specs repos now build with tox -e docs and this fails since warnings are
treated as errors. Fix issues, see below for details.

tox -e docs fails with:

1)
queens/remove-pool-group-from-zaqar.rst:402: WARNING: Inline emphasis start-string without end-string.

Fix RST syntax.

2) queens/support-md5-of-body.rst:: WARNING: document isn't included in any toctree

Include document in toctree.

3) rocky/queue-filter-support.rst:38: WARNING: Literal block expected; none found.

Fixed RST.

4) rocky/remove-format-constraint-of-client-id.rst:13: WARNING: Title overline too short.

Fixed RST.

5) rocky/remove-format-constraint-of-client-id.rst:37: ERROR: Unexpected indentation.
Fixed RST.

6) rocky/subscription-filtering-tags.rst:82: WARNING: Bullet list ends without a blank line; unexpected unindent.
Fixed RST.

Change-Id: Ide32b348d68e35f8f531c30ddae680d085553b68

subject: Remove the version option of get_session
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-08-23 02:54:11.000000000', 'message': 'Remove the version option of get_session

Actually, we have specified the version which is used to get session
when creating environment, it can not be changed because it has not
enough data for that. Also, it will create the redundant session and
save the session into cache due to change the cache key after specifying
the version 2 or 3 while creating keystone client.

Change-Id: Ia8ed56cd4beb4a47f7fe0938fbad4f4033a742ca
'}]
commit_message:
Remove the version option of get_session

Actually, we have specified the version which is used to get session
when creating environment, it can not be changed because it has not
enough data for that. Also, it will create the redundant session and
save the session into cache due to change the cache key after specifying
the version 2 or 3 while creating keystone client.

Change-Id: Ia8ed56cd4beb4a47f7fe0938fbad4f4033a742ca

commit_message:
fix ceilometer update bandwidth resource

If the user_id of the bandwidth resource is None,
the hash value of None is different on different host

This fixes the issue by filter None value from resource

Change-Id: I79dca9689bf80031341767e623a4950696a32cf3

commit_message:
Fix ceilometer polling process not able to coordinate issue

Add option start_heart=True when start partition_coordinator
to prevent old member be overwritten when new member joined group
Besides upadte member information each time before doing poll

Change-Id: I3d0acda90a57b4cb32468433f6bd593a038e76ec
Closes-Bug: #1787125
Signed-off-by: Leehom Li (feli5) <feli5@cisco.com>

commit_message:
Gate: Fix make command for osh-infra charts

This updates the make command for the osh-infra charts in the
deployment scripts to account for the charts residing in
openstack-helm-infra instead of the openstack-helm working
directory

Change-Id: I9f492e586f69b0caf908366a9cae2b55da0d4cfc

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-04-12 01:16:32.000000000', 'message': "Refactor fallocate and hole punching

Instead of having one function that either allocates space or
deallocates it, and uses either the fallocate() or posix_fallocate() C
functions for allocation, but only uses fallocate() for deallocation,
and is a no-op sometimes for allocation but never for deallocation,
let's try having two functions.

utils.fallocate(fd, size) allocates <size> bytes for the file referred
to by <fd>. It allows for keeping a reserve of an additional N bytes
or X% of the filesystem free. If neither fallocate() or
posix_fallocate() C functions are avaialble, utils.fallocate() will
log a warning (once only) and not actually allocate space.

utils.punch_hole(fd, offset, length) deallocates <length> bytes
starting at <offset> from the file referred to by <fd>. It uses the C
function fallocate(). If fallocate() is not available, calls to
utils.punch_hole() will raise an exception.

This commit also gets rid of utils.FallocateWrapper() and just has two
levels: utils.fallocate / utils.punch_hole have all the fancy logic in
them, and utils._sys_fallocate / utils._sys_posix_fallocate are just
thin wrappers around the libc functions.

Modernized the tests for utils.fallocate() and utils.punch_hole().

Change-Id: I0210a99b7f0774180937b6f8f435505b6ee151a8

Modernized the tests for utils.fallocate() and utils.punch_hole().

Change-Id: I0210a99b7f0774180937b6f8f435505b6ee151a8
"}]
commit_message:
Refactor fallocate and hole punching

Instead of having one function that either allocates space or
deallocates it, and uses either the fallocate() or posix_fallocate() C
functions for allocation, but only uses fallocate() for deallocation,
and is a no-op sometimes for allocation but never for deallocation,
let's try having two functions.

utils.fallocate(fd, size) allocates <size> bytes for the file referred
to by <fd>. It allows for keeping a reserve of an additional N bytes
or X% of the filesystem free. If neither fallocate() or
posix_fallocate() C functions are avaialble, utils.fallocate() will
log a warning (once only) and not actually allocate space.

utils.punch_hole(fd, offset, length) deallocates <length> bytes
starting at <offset> from the file referred to by <fd>. It uses the C
function fallocate(). If fallocate() is not available, calls to
utils.punch_hole() will raise an exception.

This commit also gets rid of utils.FallocateWrapper() and just has two
levels: utils.fallocate / utils.punch_hole have all the fancy logic in
them, and utils._sys_fallocate / utils._sys_posix_fallocate are just
thin wrappers around the libc functions.

Modernized the tests for utils.fallocate() and utils.punch_hole().

Change-Id: I0210a99b7f0774180937b6f8f435505b6ee151a8

commit_message:
Break dependencies on auth.controllers

Break up the direct dependencies on auth.controllers. This required
refactoring and moving of the auth controller `authenticate_for_token`
and `authenticate` methods (and associated helper methods). To avoid
needs of holding state in the helper, the MFA Validator methods were
converted to class/static methods (holding an instance of the object was
pointless). Logic will be split up/moved from auth.core in a later
patch.

NOTE the authenticate_for_token method was renamed when moved to
indicate it is webob specific. This is because both auth and
federation APIs lean on it. Conversion of federation will happen
separately from auth.

Change-Id: I1b994d777bc37f25ae92cb03c1a78d5f614ff272
Partial-Bug: #1776504

commit_message:
Add missing `xindy` bindep

Test runs are currently failing on a missing `xindy` binary.
Mend the situation by adding the required packages for rpm
and dpkg platforms.

As the test requires a recent version of `xindy` to work with
`xelatex` markup, bind the base job to a nodeset with recent
operating system release.

Change-Id: I461a8769af2a6879d1a96db13aa91fbc8ace8c54
Closes-Bug: #1792237

commit_message:
Add support for ElasticSearch 5.x

We're adding support for ElasticSearch 5.x while keeping support
for 2.x in [1]. Because ElasticSearch 2.x and 5.x require
different set of python elasticsearch library [1], I propose this
change to update the global requirement. We can support
ElasticSearch 6.x, we will need to update this again.

Requirements:
elasticsearch>=6.0.0,<7.0.0
elasticsearch>=5.0.0,<6.0.0
elasticsearch>=2.0.0,<3.0.0

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/600287/
[2] https://elasticsearch-py.readthedocs.io/en/master/#compatibility

Change-Id: I1d263ae7543f47063cccf2a5aecfe77f2f25be92
Story: #1648255
Task: #26435
Signed-off-by: Trinh Nguyen <dangtrinhnt@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Fix multipath disconnect with path failure

Under certain conditions detaching a multipath device may result on
failure when flushing one of the individual paths, but the disconnect
should have succeeded, because there were other paths available to flush
all the data.

OS-Brick is currently following standard recommended disconnect
mechanism for multipath devices:

- Release all device holders
- Flush multipath
- Flush single paths
- Delete single devices

The problem is that this procedure does an innecessary step, flushing
individual single paths, that may result in an error.

Originally it was thought that the individual flushes were necessary to
prevent data loss, but upon further study of the multipath-tools and the
device-mapper code it was discovered that this is not really the case.

After the multipath flushing has been completed we can be sure that the
data has been successfully sent and acknowledge by the device.

Closes-Bug: #1785669
Change-Id: I10f7fea2d69d5d9011f0d5486863a8d9d8a9696e
(cherry picked from commit d866ee75c23e05efee5688a948498831980d98e3)
(cherry picked from commit b253e3169625a9617a528f9f989808fb041780db)
(cherry picked from commit cd9da93ee12b1ba6145ec5b196cc02f01b84db3f)

commit_message:
Handle exceptions while monitoring VNF

If any unknown exception occurs while monitoring VNFs,
then it exits while loop where run_monitor method is
called thereby stopping VNFs monitoring completely.

Handled unknown exception and logged an error message
so that operator is aware of this issue.

Closes-Bug: #1789829
Change-Id: I0b79a0a82e984a3c9a93fc123688ccd2018cc554

commit_message:
add python 3.6 unit test job

This is a mechanically generated patch to add a unit test job running
under Python 3.6 as part of the python3-first goal.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Change-Id: Ic16433e6d23e81da7a944f2dde1befd2173aa4e6
Story: #2002586
Task: #24288

commit_message:
Demote validate-projects to non-voting

Since we changed the PTI in [1] without depending on [2]  We can't
reliably validate which projects do or do not have the
check-requirements template enabled.

We *could* grovel around in the repo and reproduce a bunch of zuul logic
for finding zuul config or we could just use this as information only
and rely on the core team to validate additions.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/571520
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/550979

Change-Id: I1a777f67031dfcff02bff1bbff66f06b1618b8a0

commit_message:
[tools/grep-all] Hide eol releases by default

As we collect more history displaying all the EOL releases becomes noise
to filter out.  Hide eol tags by default but provide a quick way to
display them again if wanted.

Change-Id: I89d0c9ae2fa2e94505d44bfa8d2e0b0f00e1d842

commit_message:
[WIP] serial console 01

Attach serial console to VMs and check for text indicating kernel bugs
(which are either kernel bugs or kernel memory corrupted by hypervisor
or host hardware).

This patch works with VirtualBox but not with KVM.

Change-Id: I8b652b8a1a9770b615ca6b2bac97f5c1b7847698

commit_message:
Only append DIB_BOOTLOADER_DEFAULT_CMDLINE to default grub entry

The grub.cfg has two variables [1]

 GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX : used on all boots
 GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT : additionally used on all "normal" boots

The problem with I2298675dda1f699c572b3423e7274bc8bd7c1c9d is that it
appened the values in DIB_BOOTLOADER_DEFAULT_CMDLINE to both of these,
resulting in duplicated arguments.  I don't think we considered that
GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT actually already appends to the
GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX values.

Make DIB_BOOTLOADER_DEFAULT_CMDLINE only append itself to
GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT.  That seems to line up sensibly with the
name of the variable.

Documentation is enhanced around this, and a releasenote added.

[1] https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Grub2/Setup

Change-Id: I76b5442a9090c19a6540ed2d4ab324546f241ebf
Closes: #1791736

commit_message:
Add patch submitting for project doc translation

Currently in propose-translation-update job for project docs are only
building of pot files included. Here we will generate and propose a
patch for:

- horizon (docs)
- openstack-ansible

commit_message:
Fix neutron dhcp log path

The neutron dhcp-agent log path is not set properly.
The service is logging at /var/log/containers/neutron/dhcp-agent.log
and the log is set to /var/log/neutron/dhcp-agent.log

Change-Id: Ia22eff1093c25395bc98cacd2f2106a2ac374eb9

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/594338/
Change-Id: I05469c61634ab1e5a450c9f04916db4ea5461ad6
Story: #2002586
Task: #24324

commit_message:
Move to london linaro mirror

I have moved nb03.o.o to the linaro-london cloud, as it should be much
more reliable in keeping it's connection to zookeeper and keeping
builds updated.  The mirror is up; switch to it for builds.

commit_message:
Test speculative gate fix

On the theory that the issue with the neutron-grenade-dvr-multinode job
is related to the switch from iptables_hybrid to the OVS firewall by
default in Rocky, try running with iptables_hybrid in Rocky for just
that job.

Change-Id: Id74926b58298912e510cb524da6b2571dc00c4ee

commit_message:
Correct elasticsearch list entropy

The list of elasticsearch hosts was being randomized too much which
results in the a performance issue. This change reduces the entropy and
ensures that the list of hosts is correctly ordered such that localhost
is always used first and other nodes in the cluster will be used as a
fall back.

Change-Id: Ifb551a6e01b5c0e1f62c1466a3d5b344a3c5da97
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Fix tools/tox_install.sh to work with current build-sphinx CI job.

Change-Id: I4a7d8047bf81ef119e085a179a7fc31b0ee78de8
Story: #2002586
Task: #24304

Follow devstack-plugin-ceph job rename

The devstack-plugin-ceph jobs have migrated to zuul v3
& in-repo and renamed[1], this commit use the new job.

Patch removing old job from openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs[2]
[1] https://review.openstack.org/543048
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/601316/

Change-Id: Ib3c71593a9fad48eb86ccc4f5c0209fbef89edb9

commit_message:
Fix unit test failure with python3.6

Since python3.6 os.path.join can be either bytes or
a str. So mock os.path.join in order for the unit tests to
pass.

Change-Id: I82c793875d888092e5c814727a6c4ad4053e76fb
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chucks@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fixes a faulty if-check

Constructs a list object from a filter object; previously, the
if would always resolve as true because a FilterObject was being
checked.

Change-Id: Ie88b81019cc05d4a454ac1c2ddc0e05a86a1c2ae
closes-bug: #1791602

commit_message:
Display users with role through group in users project details tab.

In the users tab of the project details view, the users
table displays now the users which have a role on the project
through a group. ie: if a group is member of the project, and
if a user is a member of this group, then it will be displayed
in the table even if it is not directly a member of the project.

An extra column is added to the table: "role from group" which
display the list of "role(group)" the user has on the project.

To be able to test the membership of user to a project through
a group, "user_group_membership" data has been added to keystone
data.

Change-Id: I968bad7d285acfaf7a8ccd7458593bbcad498ce2
Partial-Bug: #1785263

commit_message:
libvirt: Always escape IPv6 addresses when used in migration URI

If IPv6 is passed to URI it should be wrapped within square brackets.
This patch detects IPv6 to form migration URI properly. Domain name, IPv4 or
already bracketed IPv6 address will pass as is

Extend tests to include collapsed IPv6 addresses and IPv6 addresses with
port

Change-Id: I1201db996ea6ceaebd49479b298d74585a78b006
Closes-Bug: #1786058
(cherry picked from commit 8b019d6f1e7893a7e308bd79c879e94d3400e007)

commit_message:
Add ability to test Manila UI with Horizon master branch

For the developers needs it's useful to be able run tests with the
latest Horizon version from the master branch.

This patch introduces new tox environment py3-dev to run tests with the
Horizon master branch.

By default, Horizon will be installed from the master branch of it's git
repository. You can override this behaviour by setting HORIZON_REPO
environment variable to test the plugin with your local copy.

Change-Id: Iea6e53eb38ac82817ad893770316db49c141644a

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Update tools/tox_install.sh to work with current CI build-sphinx job.

Change-Id: I69290fae418a98038f01893a36ba549654a56556
Story: #2002586
Task: #24304

commit_message:
Use templates for cover and lower-constraints

Use openstack-tox-cover template, this runs the cover job
in the check queue only.

Use openstack-lower-constraints-jobs template.

Remove jobs that are part of the templates.

Move template list to top of project stanza to follow common practice
and sort list of templates.

Change-Id: Iaa754888d1c6fbe6a563098507c1eb71300ab845

commit_message:
Reduce qos rpc times on the ovs-agent side

When multiple ports are bound to qos-policy with the same id,
ovs-agent should check whether the cache has policy information
instead of directly reading rpc when processing the port.

Change-Id: I88f9f5af95439f1536799169390764c89109f467
Closes-Bug: #1783559
(cherry picked from commit 7a27e24447cf519796cb39532e719ed66f6bcb3d)

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-09-12 15:54:49.000000000', 'message': 'Add writer method to DiskFile

DiskFile already exposes a reader method that creates the DiskFileReader
instance. Add a writer method for parity.

DiskFile currently only provides a context manager create - that will
open and close the DiskFileWriter.  Add explicit open and close methods
to support more flexibility in how callers manage life-cycle on their
DiskFileWriter instances.

Diskfile confusingly manages some state for DiskFileWriter (e.g. fd,
tmppath, use_linkat).  Encapsulate the DiskFileWriter state to improve
readability and reduce coupling (e.g. put_succeeced).

Change-Id: If18e0041680470a9c57a08e9ea9327acba8593df
'}]
commit_message:
Add writer method to DiskFile

DiskFile already exposes a reader method that creates the DiskFileReader
instance. Add a writer method for parity.

DiskFile currently only provides a context manager create - that will
open and close the DiskFileWriter.  Add explicit open and close methods
to support more flexibility in how callers manage life-cycle on their
DiskFileWriter instances.

Diskfile confusingly manages some state for DiskFileWriter (e.g. fd,
tmppath, use_linkat).  Encapsulate the DiskFileWriter state to improve
readability and reduce coupling (e.g. put_succeeced).

Change-Id: If18e0041680470a9c57a08e9ea9327acba8593df

commit_message:
Modify Pure driver to configure PG/Pod names

Add two config options to the Pure Storage driver to allow setting the
names for replication PGs and Pods. This is beneficial in multi-backend
scenarios so that each backend can use a different PG/Pod. It also
allows for the use of existing PGs/Pods.

These options should not be modified after volumes exist on a backend.

Change-Id: Ie0dbf00fb2ecea3344e58d2b84fd4dfd6ae1daee

commit_message:
Add AllNodesExtraMapData parameter

The AllNodesExtraMapData parameter is used to inject additional
hieradata into the all_nodes hierdata file on each node. The injected
data will be deeploy merged with the calculated all_nodes data for the
stack.

The parameter can be taken advantage of for split-controlplane use cases
where the hieradata from the control stack needs to be populated into
the separate compute stacks.

To easily get the hieradata out of the control stack, a new stack output
is added, AllNodesConfig.

Partially Implements: blueprint split-controlplane

Change-Id: I7b865bf82520006eef3ac2f36df34b1f3c34e642

repository.

specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:

commit_message:
Fix py36 unit tests

While running the unit tests under python3.6 the response and expected
results were not matching up entirely correctly compared to older
versions of python. Instead, parse the JSON response and compare it to
the expected value as a dictionary.

Change-Id: I72f882e870d5671ba02e4d429be1cb12d97c46c2
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chucks@redhat.com>

commit_message:
WIP: Add CI/development block devices environment files

Provide dev-block-devices.yaml so that developers or
CI jobs may use it to have a preboot script create a
virtual block device to use with ceph-ansible (which
requires a block device).

Adding directly to Pike branch in order to use with
quickstart featureset024, which tests upgrades from
Pike to Queens on OVB.

Change-Id: I8e3ea1b5ea7d9128183d1f4d7729035c36efba4c
Related-Bug: #1772034
Depends-On: I382ff788ac7af6bef66d1661c0b8927572025db7

commit_message:
Use uuidsentinel from oslo.utils

A recent nova change [1] removing uuidsentinel (which is now found
in oslo.utils) broke our UTs. This changes our code to use
oslo.utils, fixing the issue.

[1] 8e1ca5bf34f924b9a23ddbcf31ae727a7dcacb20

Change-Id: Ic314f975c4206a73d2ddd3608181cddc43604f59

I haven't checked where we apply policy enforcement.
As of now, we have two policy enforcer: neutron_lib._policy and neutron.policy. neutron.policy is used in the pecan hooks [1].

I am wondering whether we need to merge two policy enforcer or not.
Anyway I will continue to investigate the code.

daidv will help the policy-in-code efforts too.

[{'created': '2017-12-12 01:17:35.000000000', 'message': "framework for policy-in-code support in neutron stadium

Policy-in-code support in neutron stadium is a bit different from
other projects as the neutron server needs to load policies in code
from multiple projects. This commit sets up the framework to support
policy-in-code in the stadium projects.

Each stadium project should register the following two entry points:
named oslo.policy.policies and neutron.policies in setup.cfg.

oslo.policy.policies =
    neutron = neutron.conf.policies:list_rules
neutron.policies =
    neutron = neutron.conf.policies:list_rules

The above two entries are same, but they have different purposes.

* The first entry point is a normal entry point defined by oslo.policy
  and it is used to generate a sample policy file [1].
* The second one is specific to the neutron stadium. It is used by
  neutron-lib policy module to load policies of stadium related projects.
  oslo.policy.policies entry point is used by all projects which
  adopt oslo.policy, so we cannot determine which projects are
  neutron stadium projects, so the second entry point is required.

The recommended entry point name is a repository name:
For example, 'neutron-fwaas' for FWaaS and 'networking-sfc' for SFC.

Except registering 'neutron.policies' entry point, other steps to be
done in each stadium project for policy-in-code are same for all
OpenStack projects.

Examples:
neutron: Ib8be61ffcbd10a893f47d35c09456700f803816e
neutron-fwaas: I67be3a21f19e3f793312d64d358452ee4531c080

oslo.policy.enforcer entry point is registered by neutron-lib.
It is used to genarate a merged policy file [2], so it is natural to
register it by neutron-lib.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/oslo.policy/latest/user/usage.html#sample-file-generation
[2] https://docs.openstack.org/oslo.policy/latest/user/usage.html#merged-file-generation

TODO (as neutron stadium)
* Check the default in-code policy works as expected
* Check overriding the default policy by policy file
* Check overriding the default policy by policy_dirs mechanism

TODO (in neutron-lib)
* Write test code with neutron.policies fixture
* Write a documentation on policy-in-code support

TODO (in each stadium project)
* Convert an existing policy.json into in-code policy
* Use policy.DocumentedRuleDefault rather than policy.RuleDefault
* Generate policy sample in the documentation
* Remove existing policy.json
* Remove policy.json for testing and use in-code policy for testing

Change-Id: I6f8f8555e8560bbd66f5b033e7aed95c1138cf5c

commit_message:
framework for policy-in-code support in neutron stadium

Policy-in-code support in neutron stadium is a bit different from
other projects as the neutron server needs to load policies in code
from multiple projects. This commit sets up the framework to support
policy-in-code in the stadium projects.

Each stadium project should register the following two entry points:
named oslo.policy.policies and neutron.policies in setup.cfg.

oslo.policy.policies =
    neutron = neutron.conf.policies:list_rules
neutron.policies =
    neutron = neutron.conf.policies:list_rules

The above two entries are same, but they have different purposes.

* The first entry point is a normal entry point defined by oslo.policy
  and it is used to generate a sample policy file [1].
* The second one is specific to the neutron stadium. It is used by
  neutron-lib policy module to load policies of stadium related projects.
  oslo.policy.policies entry point is used by all projects which
  adopt oslo.policy, so we cannot determine which projects are
  neutron stadium projects, so the second entry point is required.

The recommended entry point name is a repository name:
For example, 'neutron-fwaas' for FWaaS and 'networking-sfc' for SFC.

Except registering 'neutron.policies' entry point, other steps to be
done in each stadium project for policy-in-code are same for all
OpenStack projects.

Examples:
neutron: Ib8be61ffcbd10a893f47d35c09456700f803816e
neutron-fwaas: I67be3a21f19e3f793312d64d358452ee4531c080

oslo.policy.enforcer entry point is registered by neutron-lib.

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Change-Id: I5a2eb250169af97583b3ee5801063327197f150c
Story: #2002586
Task: #24309

commit_message:
Allow overriding the default default_soa_expire

Designate upstream has a shorter default value of SOA expire as
86400s=1d than RFC 1912 suggestion (2-4 weeks). So allow tweaking the
default value per operational needs.

Change-Id: I668a4470be612e596ab4db73ece0c37269c88005
Closes-Bug: #1784272

commit_message:
Fix Python3.5+ issues

The driver was relying on attributes such as "im_class" that does not
exist in Python3+ anymore.

This patch fixes those problems and also add a new job in the gate to
exercise tempest with Python3.5+ so those errors don't sneak in the
code again.

Closes-Bug: #1791925
Change-Id: I8686288bd4493f56b25e99281999bdd5e1296f8c

I'm not sure I like this. Sure, it eases upgrades, but at the expense of new clusters. This will require that the long-term config be longer, while making it easier to stand up a new cluster where you *think* encryption is enabled, but it actually *isn't*.

I'm still debating about whether I object enough to block it, though, so no vote."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2016-07-05 18:05:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I agree with Tim, existing default is better for new clusters.  Terrible precedent for new functionality to say you have to add this middleware and *also* turn it on.  Expectation should be that if you put encryption is in the pipeline you get encrypted data at rest.

If you're upgrading, and you put encryption in the pipeline but don't read the docs - there's a race with un-restarted proxies encountering encrypted data recently uploaded through an encrypted proxy - but that should be short lived and you eventually get encrypted data at rest.

If we change the default and you put encryption in the pipeline but don't read the docs - the race is unbounded "you don't get encrypted until you change your configs" - you may never get to encrypted data at rest - or worse some unencrypted data sneaks into a new "encrypted" cluster and there's no way to discover what needs to be fixed!

Principle of least harm seems to favor default of True.  Even less risky if we don't recommend adding encryption to existing clusters until have a better story for sandboxing and/or migration.'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2016-07-06 00:26:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Tim and Clay,

Fair enough. Exactly, changing default may make a new cluster deployment complicated. But I'm still worried the upgrading impact  yet, tbh. so... on my second idea, instead of this, how about

- Adding logger to encryption middleware to say "encryption is enabled" at proxy restarting. This would make it easy to find unfortunate turning on of encryption staff.
 
- Then, adding one more note at Upgrading Consideration section in docs like "NOTE: disable_encryption = False in default so at item 3, you should remove the comment out in proxy-server.conf and set disable_encryption = True explicitly"


Thought?


Mahati,

Thanks for reviewing! Now I'm on second idea as above. Howe do you feel like it?'}, {'account_id': 12261, 'date': '2016-07-07 11:08:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

It's correct that new cluster deployment will be easier, I also like kota's suggested alternative of adding a note and logger msg.

But the point on reading docs- I think they'd have to read docs anyway in order to know *where* to put encryption in the pipeline and it wouldn't be too hard to miss out one "disable_encryption" part.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-08-11 23:29:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Change encryption default to disabled=True

Regarding to "Upgrading Consideration" for encryption docs[1], the docs
says "3. Add keymaster and encryption middlewares to every proxy server’s
middleware pipeline with the encryption disable_encryption option set to
True and the keymaster encryption_root_secret value set as described
above"

However, current disable_encryption option is False in default so
operators may deploy encryption staff as enabled when just inserting the
middlewares with default proxy-server.conf.

To avoid this unfortunately enabled (but not ready actually) situation,
this patch changes the default as disabled=True. Operators should remove
the comment out and change the option to False for applying encryption
available explicitly.

I know this patch will conflict with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/336618/
and it's ok to wait it lands first. I can rebase easily for that.

Change-Id: I71f53c83fbe5296fbbdd10d5dbde1446c9bc1823
1: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/overview_encryption.html#upgrade-considerations

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-16 12:26:21.000000000', 'message': "Fix object-expirer to prevent orphaned objects

Current object-expirer regards PreconditionFailed as
success status and expirer will remove the item from queue.

However, imagine the split brain case with 3 replicas for an object like:

t[n] means timestamp.

t1: a object w/o x-delete-at
t2: a object w/ x-delete-at for t3

Assuming:
t1 < t2 < t3

|-primaries-|-handoffs-|
[t1, t1, t1, t2, t2, t2]

and if object-expirer works against to primaries before object-replicator
resolving the split brain, DELETE t1 objects will return 412
PreconditionFailed and object-expirer will pop the object from its queue.

After that, object-replicator will copy t2 from handoffs to primaries
and then a client will get 404 Not Found after t3 but t2 objects will never
be deleted on actual devices and also the container won't be updated as
deleted.

To prevent such a condition, this patch changes the object-server
to return 409 for older DELETE request than current object. The 409
will be handled as an exception at object-expirer and object-expirer will
not get rid of the object from its queue until the conflicted status
resolved.

TODO:
- create prob test for proof

Change-Id: I0b955c125063e545828c41c06fa7155f1d1b91bf
"}]
commit_message:
Fix object-expirer to prevent orphaned objects

Current object-expirer regards PreconditionFailed as
success status and expirer will remove the item from queue.

However, imagine the split brain case with 3 replicas for an object like:

t[n] means timestamp.

t1: a object w/o x-delete-at
t2: a object w/ x-delete-at for t3

Assuming:
t1 < t2 < t3

|-primaries-|-handoffs-|
[t1, t1, t1, t2, t2, t2]

and if object-expirer works against to primaries before object-replicator
resolving the split brain, DELETE t1 objects will return 412
PreconditionFailed and object-expirer will pop the object from its queue.

After that, object-replicator will copy t2 from handoffs to primaries
and then a client will get 404 Not Found after t3 but t2 objects will never
be deleted on actual devices and also the container won't be updated as
deleted.

To prevent such a condition, this patch changes the object-server
to return 409 for older DELETE request than current object. The 409
will be handled as an exception at object-expirer and object-expirer will
not get rid of the object from its queue until the conflicted status
resolved.

TODO:
- create prob test for proof

Change-Id: I0b955c125063e545828c41c06fa7155f1d1b91bf

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-05 01:57:30.000000000', 'message': "Refactor versioned_writes middleware

This is a follow up patch for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/134347/
(But not want to squash because mainly this focuses on just refactoring)

This patch mainly includes a couple of refactor as follows:

- Configuration handling:

To make versioned_writes middleware more intuitive, this patch refactors
to move all 'allow_versioned_writes' option handling (i.e.
configured/enabled/disabled) into the entry __call__ method.

This enables to check the versioned_writes middleware turned
on/off/not-configured before actual versioning process and to clarify
which method should be called on the state. It will prevent to make
mis-maintained state in configurations.

- container_request method:

This patch changes container_request to use Request/Response instead of
env/start_response as well as any other method in the middleware. That's
because the change enable to leave header handling to swob. If we use it,
we don't have to consider raw wsgi header specifications. In addition,
if we could expect that both container_request and object_request returns
an Response instance (or self.app), we can simplify the code to call
resp(env, start_response) at the end of __call__()

*bonus*
- Add table document from thiago to be able to consider which configurable
  state we have to maintain in versioned_writes middleware.
- Fix some nits weird fake responses in units

Change-Id: I525505b3a4b53a7df23fa53da9a128513a5ea9a0

commit_message:
Refactor versioned_writes middleware

This is a follow up patch for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/134347/
(But not want to squash because mainly this focuses on just refactoring)

This patch mainly includes a couple of refactor as follows:

- Configuration handling:

To make versioned_writes middleware more intuitive, this patch refactors
to move all 'allow_versioned_writes' option handling (i.e.
configured/enabled/disabled) into the entry __call__ method.

This enables to check the versioned_writes middleware turned
on/off/not-configured before actual versioning process and to clarify
which method should be called on the state. It will prevent to make
mis-maintained state in configurations.

- container_request method:

This patch changes container_request to use Request/Response instead of
env/start_response as well as any other method in the middleware. That's
because the change enable to leave header handling to swob. If we use it,
we don't have to consider raw wsgi header specifications. In addition,
if we could expect that both container_request and object_request returns
an Response instance (or self.app), we can simplify the code to call
resp(env, start_response) at the end of __call__()

*bonus*
- Add table document from thiago to be able to consider which configurable
  state we have to maintain in versioned_writes middleware.
- Fix some nits weird fake responses in units

Change-Id: I525505b3a4b53a7df23fa53da9a128513a5ea9a0

commit_message:
Add more test for test_byteswapped_serialization

This is a follow up for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/395237

That patch attempt to resolve a problem when operator deploys
a ring built in different endianess machine. This patch adds more
assertions to make sure the new ring info structure including byteorder
and the backward compatibility.

Change-Id: I7a291603346fe1b6da993103572d97cbf421b1a4

The option ha_vrrp_health_check_interval [1] can re-trigger
the election process until a master is re-elected when multiple
masters problem appear. This is an important feature that enables
the system to recover automatically, we should enable it.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/ocata/networking-guide/ \
        deploy-ovs-ha-vrrp.html#keepalived-vrrp-health-check

Closes-Bug: 1732154
'}]
commit_message:
Enable keepalived VRRP health check

The option ha_vrrp_health_check_interval [1] can re-trigger
the election process until a master is re-elected when multiple
masters problem appear. This is an important feature that enables
the system to recover automatically, we should enable it.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/ocata/networking-guide/ \
        deploy-ovs-ha-vrrp.html#keepalived-vrrp-health-check

Change-Id: Iaf15ac77e249d1fe4a5101068761302e53385642
Closes-Bug: 1732154

commit_message:
Eliminate node_index in Putter

That is because putters don't have to know the node index.

Basically, a Putter is assigned for each backend object server
and the info the Putter needs is only frag_index to push it down as
X-Object-Sysmeta-Ec-Frag-Index.

This change requires a parent patch that enable get_put_connection
method to take a primary_nodes args. Maybe this patch is able to squash
into there.

Change-Id: I837f926b3f81e3b163d4c2594a7517f72170a6f1

commit_message:
Update docs for live_migration_progress_timeout option

Change I1a1143ddf8da5fb9706cf53dbfd6cbe84e606ae1 in Ocata
deprecated the libvirt.live_migration_progress_timeout
and disabled it by default. This change updates the config
option help to refer to the bug so people don't have to hunt
for it via git history, and also touches up the admin docs.
In the one doc, mention of the option is removed altogether
because it basically says, "here is a loaded gun, but don't
use it!". It's better to just not mention the option at all.

Change-Id: I33f3d508a2af6c94435f86ac740cf24b97dba76e
Related-Bug: #1644248

commit_message:
Add logging_error_fixture to functional tests

The fixture will cause a formatting error when writing logs
to be raised as an exception (thus failing tests).

In the non-gabbi tests the fixture is started in the normal way
with useFixture. In the gabbi tests the fixture setUp and
cleanUp is done manually because the fixtures start and stop
per yaml file, not per test.

Change-Id: Ia5094c3a12bcb9d19d429fbe2164b4533ca9c715

commit_message:
Demote validate-projects to non-voting

Since we changed the PTI in [1] without depending on [2]  We can't
reliably validate which projects do or do not have the
check-requirements template enabled.

We *could* grovel around in the repo and reproduce a bunch of zuul logic
for finding zuul config or we could just use this as information only
and rely on the core team to validate additions.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/571520
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/550979

Change-Id: I1a777f67031dfcff02bff1bbff66f06b1618b8a0
(cherry picked from commit 996c2788b5a58da3bc9fd9620e5f405719b41bd8)

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.

Change-Id: If5bea7f1c27a8ea6d2d0f89f59019197f9204677
(cherry picked from commit 9156a8554a47f8c7a95cd7ebc9529d0bcf3370fc)

commit_message:
Revert "Change log hashing to SHA256"

We should exempt previous releases from this check. We
should not change the behavior in a backport.

This also adds nosec comment since this usage of sha1 is
confined to log hashing.

This reverts commit 52822f1c11fc7dc1a3fe5001691f2f05eeac20d9.

Change-Id: I8b2a479ee929f85d19fbea76ff082b725fc50e81

commit_message:
add python 3.6 unit test job

This is a mechanically generated patch to add a unit test job running
under Python 3.6 as part of the python3-first goal.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Note that python36 fails installing nodejs-legacy since bionic does not
include it. Install nodejs-legacy only on Xenial.

Change-Id: Id8fbe2d5188054924eacb74bcfc52b49fd8a1d84
Story: #2002586
Task: #24327

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.
2. We promote the openstack-ansible-functional-opensuse-423
   job given that it is passing consistently.

Change-Id: I92cf6959544a9f8af8c207d6ff17eff18a8a242d
(cherry picked from commit e5cd133aeb0e48a29aef8413dfdbb05b02c9ae6c)

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/598346/
Change-Id: I0683619ee09aca4f7ea7474f61826dbb9607a6ab
Story: #2002586
Task: #24304

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.
2. We promote the distro_install jobs, given that they are
   all now working.

Change-Id: Ie5d4221f84f30f0476b089cb5144c902b4b07f52
(cherry picked from commit f327c0eedec90a5be2f3951513ce78c5dec7e9f0)

subject: strategy: linear: Inspect the delegated host on delegated tasks.
messages: [{'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2018-09-11 21:36:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked from branch master.'}, {'account_id': 17799, 'date': '2018-09-11 21:43:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:\n\ncheck experimental'}, {'account_id': 23163, 'date': '2018-09-12 07:15:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2018-09-12 16:19:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-09-11 21:36:35.000000000', 'message': 'strategy: linear: Inspect the delegated host on delegated tasks.

The purpose of the 'physical_host_addrs' variable was to create a
mapping with all the physical hosts and their IP addresses. However,
the function was broken because it used the 'physical_host' task
variable to obtain the name of the physical host for the running task.
As such, the dictionary only contained a single entry. This breaks
delegation between hosts, since there was no entry in the dictionary for
the delegated host. So if a task targetting containerA on hostA was
delegated to containerB on hostB, the IP address of the hostB was not
in the dictionary. The connection plugin code then used the 'hostB'
hostname to connect to the host instead of its IP. However, if there
is no central DNS to translate hostB to an IP or if the deployer
did not add such mapping to /etc/hosts we observed the following
problem.

fatal: [compute00]: UNREACHABLE! => {"changed": false, "msg": "Failed to connect to the host via ssh: ssh:
Could not resolve hostname controller00: Name or service not known\r\n", "unreachable": true}

In order to fix that, we now examine the delegated host and create the
appropriate mappings if the task is delegated. This ensures that the

commit_message:
strategy: linear: Inspect the delegated host on delegated tasks.

The purpose of the 'physical_host_addrs' variable was to create a
mapping with all the physical hosts and their IP addresses. However,
the function was broken because it used the 'physical_host' task
variable to obtain the name of the physical host for the running task.
As such, the dictionary only contained a single entry. This breaks
delegation between hosts, since there was no entry in the dictionary for
the delegated host. So if a task targetting containerA on hostA was
delegated to containerB on hostB, the IP address of the hostB was not
in the dictionary. The connection plugin code then used the 'hostB'
hostname to connect to the host instead of its IP. However, if there
is no central DNS to translate hostB to an IP or if the deployer
did not add such mapping to /etc/hosts we observed the following
problem.

fatal: [compute00]: UNREACHABLE! => {"changed": false, "msg": "Failed to connect to the host via ssh: ssh:
Could not resolve hostname controller00: Name or service not known\r\n", "unreachable": true}

In order to fix that, we now examine the delegated host and create the
appropriate mappings if the task is delegated. This ensures that the
physical_host_addrs variable also contains information for the delegated
hosts instead of just the original one.

Change-Id: Ic84ad3ccdd8283a4ab3fb3130d4d5e520ab736de
(cherry picked from commit f56d1242c99f68659e575aa610cdefff73e7707a)

commit_message:
Allow performing Ceph update/upgrade separately

Running `openstack overcloud external-update run` will update all
external services. This commit adds possibility of running `openstack
overcloud external-update run --tags ceph` to specifically update just
Ceph. It works analogically for upgrades.

Change-Id: Ic1786b6dbfa54516bfb836b450fc35452dca8cb5
Partial-Bug: #1783949
(cherry picked from commit 4504aadef69fc2366d3e959e1460138c85ec6ab2)

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.

Change-Id: I2c7c0e1e682e24f15270d4c81b62dc927a766a3f
(cherry picked from commit f0c0607bc542004dd0434620581947e9e8fe67ad)

commit_message:
strategy: linear: Inspect the delegated host on delegated tasks.

The purpose of the 'physical_host_addrs' variable was to create a
mapping with all the physical hosts and their IP addresses. However,
the function was broken because it used the 'physical_host' task
variable to obtain the name of the physical host for the running task.
As such, the dictionary only contained a single entry. This breaks
delegation between hosts, since there was no entry in the dictionary for
the delegated host. So if a task targetting containerA on hostA was
delegated to containerB on hostB, the IP address of the hostB was not
in the dictionary. The connection plugin code then used the 'hostB'
hostname to connect to the host instead of its IP. However, if there
is no central DNS to translate hostB to an IP or if the deployer
did not add such mapping to /etc/hosts we observed the following
problem.

fatal: [compute00]: UNREACHABLE! => {"changed": false, "msg": "Failed to connect to the host via ssh: ssh:
Could not resolve hostname controller00: Name or service not known\r\n", "unreachable": true}

In order to fix that, we now examine the delegated host and create the
appropriate mappings if the task is delegated. This ensures that the
physical_host_addrs variable also contains information for the delegated
hosts instead of just the original one.

Change-Id: Ic84ad3ccdd8283a4ab3fb3130d4d5e520ab736de
(cherry picked from commit f56d1242c99f68659e575aa610cdefff73e7707a)

commit_message:
import zuul job settings from project-config

This is a mechanically generated patch to complete step 1 of moving
the zuul job settings out of project-config and into each project
repository.

Because there will be a separate patch on each branch, the branch
specifiers for branch-specific jobs have been removed.

Because this patch is generated by a script, there may be some
cosmetic changes to the layout of the YAML file(s) as the contents are
normalized.

See the python3-first goal document for details:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/stein/python3-first.html

Change-Id: Ib925cd3bc61d8d8f1f84f7f5b79662d85d344754
Story: #2002586
Task: #24324

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.
2. We promote the distro_install jobs, given that they are
   all now working.

Change-Id: If1c1cbb25cef257c239b507581e27b9ba6c59d96
(cherry picked from commit 65c245ec695d741a1803f79a1feabb6c616ce490)

commit_message:
defaults: Bump mariadb to 10.2 release branch

mariadb 10.2 was first released in April 2016 and OpenStack services
should be ready to use it by now, so lets switch to 10.2. For mariadb
10.2 we need to use xtrabackup-24. This version is not available in Leap
42.3 so we add an extra OBS repository for it.

Change-Id: I5f1aaf1f8608ad085acfebc8458910391f280193

[{'created': '2018-09-11 21:37:02.000000000', 'message': 'strategy: linear: Inspect the delegated host on delegated tasks.

The purpose of the 'physical_host_addrs' variable was to create a
mapping with all the physical hosts and their IP addresses. However,
the function was broken because it used the 'physical_host' task
variable to obtain the name of the physical host for the running task.
As such, the dictionary only contained a single entry. This breaks
delegation between hosts, since there was no entry in the dictionary for
the delegated host. So if a task targetting containerA on hostA was
delegated to containerB on hostB, the IP address of the hostB was not
in the dictionary. The connection plugin code then used the 'hostB'
hostname to connect to the host instead of its IP. However, if there
is no central DNS to translate hostB to an IP or if the deployer
did not add such mapping to /etc/hosts we observed the following
problem.

fatal: [compute00]: UNREACHABLE! => {"changed": false, "msg": "Failed to connect to the host via ssh: ssh:
Could not resolve hostname controller00: Name or service not known\r\n", "unreachable": true}

In order to fix that, we now examine the delegated host and create the
appropriate mappings if the task is delegated. This ensures that the
physical_host_addrs variable also contains information for the delegated
hosts instead of just the original one.

Change-Id: Ic84ad3ccdd8283a4ab3fb3130d4d5e520ab736de
(cherry picked from commit f56d1242c99f68659e575aa610cdefff73e7707a)

commit_message:
strategy: linear: Inspect the delegated host on delegated tasks.

The purpose of the 'physical_host_addrs' variable was to create a
mapping with all the physical hosts and their IP addresses. However,
the function was broken because it used the 'physical_host' task
variable to obtain the name of the physical host for the running task.
As such, the dictionary only contained a single entry. This breaks
delegation between hosts, since there was no entry in the dictionary for
the delegated host. So if a task targetting containerA on hostA was
delegated to containerB on hostB, the IP address of the hostB was not
in the dictionary. The connection plugin code then used the 'hostB'
hostname to connect to the host instead of its IP. However, if there
is no central DNS to translate hostB to an IP or if the deployer
did not add such mapping to /etc/hosts we observed the following
problem.

fatal: [compute00]: UNREACHABLE! => {"changed": false, "msg": "Failed to connect to the host via ssh: ssh:
Could not resolve hostname controller00: Name or service not known\r\n", "unreachable": true}

In order to fix that, we now examine the delegated host and create the
appropriate mappings if the task is delegated. This ensures that the
physical_host_addrs variable also contains information for the delegated
hosts instead of just the original one.

Change-Id: Ic84ad3ccdd8283a4ab3fb3130d4d5e520ab736de
(cherry picked from commit f56d1242c99f68659e575aa610cdefff73e7707a)

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We revert the use of project templates to using job config
   directly, given that nothing other than Ubuntu Xenial/Bionic
   is currently working.
2. We remove the opensuse-150 tests, as they are not passing,
   nor have they since their inception.

Change-Id: I37a9f2af33d47a8edd5788d1504bb2c956356235
(cherry picked from commit bf83323e97483f42315664c566d8806678eb59e7)

commit_message:
Produce mount volume only if OVS_HOST_PATH is defined

In case of empty $OVS_HOST_PATH
tools/generate_k8s_resource_definitions generates incorrect
cni_ds.yaml.

openvswitch mount volume is necessary for ovn use case
and maybe for vhostuser use case.

So it's better to omit it when $OVS_HOST_PATH is empty.

Closes-Bug: #1791266
Change-Id: Ieed08a998f1b7e348428ab16e53d9072ca7b9e73
Signed-off-by: Alexey Perevalov <a.perevalov@samsung.com>
(cherry picked from commit 027a17f1ede835d37612833206db12f814d0f1a4)

commit_message:
Clean up role tests

Now that we're using the general templates, we can slim down
the role test definitions. We can also remove tests which are
not being watched, or which are fundamentally broken. With
this we can also remove unused scripts/plays.

We do the following:

1. We remove the 'ssl' job, given that the person working on
   that is no longer doing so, and no-one else has picked up
   the work.
2. We revert the use of project templates to using job config
   directly, given that nothing other than Ubuntu is supported.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/600906
Change-Id: Icc88c81c5c8247a4f511819d38b08ac1cf5262e5

commit_message:
Filter leases by project_id

Added to the Leases list V2 REST API the project_id query param.
This parameter filters the leases returned during a lease list.
Only admin users are capable of filtering leases by any project.
A regular user only can filter by his/her own project.

Change-Id: Ief872d76aabb1f3109d3520a4b68c1087c684f5c
Closes-Bug: #1306231
Closes-Bug: #1299122

- gate-swift-dsvm-functional-identity-v3-only-ubuntu-xenial-nv http://logs.openstack.org/03/396603/1/check/gate-swift-dsvm-functional-identity-v3-only-ubuntu-xenial-nv/085362c/ : SUCCESS in 20m 30s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2016-11-11 18:42:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thinking about this a bit, my expectation upon copying a delete marker would be to either

* 404, because it represents a thing that isn't there, or
* succeed in creating a new zero-byte object, but without the ";swift_versions_deleted=1" param in the content-type.

The key thing for versioned_writes, and the reason that I went with a content-type that included a ";swift*" param, was to have a way to know this object was created by versioned_writes as the result of a DELETE. I don't think anything else should trigger the crazy special-case behavior when in stack mode (see https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/2.10.0/swift/common/middleware/versioned_writes.py#L578-L621).

I remember distinctly thinking about some of the problems that may arise from users interacting with delete markers, in particular when POSTing to them. I decided that if you start messing with this thing like it's a regular object, we should treat it like a regular object.

So I guess I might be leaning towards the second option above? But maybe it's worth getting more opinions on this; I know neither of those is useful for the problem you're trying to solve. Joel in particular may have some thoughts on the interaction between COPY and ;swift content-types, so I'll add him as a reviewer.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-11-18 13:16:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

The reason why I call this is WIP because delete-marker may not be designed to be copied to other containers so we need to clarify what's specification in the Swift API."}]

commit_message:
WIP: Allowing copy objects which has special content type

I'm not sure if this is really a bug or just expected specification.

When using Versioned Write middleware with History mode, we can generate
delete-marker object in the history-location container which means the
deleted at that time. It can be used as a normal object with 0 bytes for
client.

However, when calling COPY (or PUT with x-copy-from or POST in
post_as_copy) for the object, the client can see 400 Bad Request due to
the special content type includes ';'.

This patch attempts to allow the copy requests to store the objects as
they are.

Change-Id: Idc8ae04d714f5f826d8ab508a87ad93e72093ac5
